```

Hi mbostock,

I'm currently playing with your fantastic lib, trying to graphically represent prototypal inheritance between javascript objects.

The principle is to consider objects as nodes and prototypes as links, eg:

``` javascript
//         (0)
//       /  |  \
//     (1) (2) (3)
//    /   \
// (1.1) (1.2)

zero = root = {};
  one = Object.create(zero);
    oneOne = Object.create(one);
    oneTwo = Object.create(one);
  two = Object.create(zero);
  three = Object.create(zero);

data = [zero, one, oneOne, oneTwo, two, three];
```

as tree's children function, I just use:

``` javascript
var tree = d3.layout.tree()
  .children(function (d) {
    var children;

    return (children = data.filter(function (el) {return Object.getPrototypeOf(el) === d;})).length && children || null;
  });
```
## 

Trying to compute nodes from it, I was faced to infinite recursive loops, for example with [d3_layout_treeVisitAfter](https://github.com/mbostock/d3/blob/master/d3.layout.js#L1620) because `node.children` if didn't exist on a leaf was retrieved from the prototype chain.

``` javascript
nodes = tree.nodes(root);
```

In the previous example, `oneOne` is a leaf so does not have `children`. As a consequence when assigning `children = node.children`, `children` will be retrieved from the prototype chain and `one.children` will be the result => **infinite loop**

You can have _a live example on what's going wrong_ [here](http://jsfiddle.net/abernier/6WePy/show/) in the console.

In order to address this issue, I patch some files in order to restrict `children`'s access only to the object that owns the property, thus avoiding prototype chain retrieval — mainly with `hasOwnProperty`.

_It seems to work_: http://jsfiddle.net/abernier/6WePy/1/show/

I've also test it does not break `examples` and tests.

I let you review the code hoping you'll merge it :)

Cheers
